             who married the prisoner, was my niece. I have not seen her for ten years, and have made every enquiry.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18201028-68-person770">
                  WILLIAM 
                  GORDON
               <interp inst="t18201028-68-person770" type="surname" value="GORDON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18201028-68-person770" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18201028-68-person770" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the prisoner's brother. Miss Lawes lived in my house at Woolwich. He was about to marry her - I only knew of his intent ten days before the marriage deed was executed. Before that I made diligent enquiry for his first wife of Mrs. Brooks and Jones, at his particular request. Miss Lawes knew he was a widower - it was occasionally a topic of conversation, for they were in my house a month before they were married. My brother told me his wife ran away from him in 1813. Miss Lawes was present at her sister's death.</p>

               <p>MR. ALLEY. Q. How long was that young lady in your house before he married her - A. About a month, and my wife had known her thirty years; in fact Miss Lawes was a tenant of mine some years ago. I made the enquiry about the years 1814 and 1815, not since. I never mentioned to Miss Lawes that my brother was about to marry her sister - they were acquainted about a month before they were married.</p>
               <p>MR. ADOLPHUS. Q. Did you know whether they agreed to marry at first meeting - A. They walked out daily.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. As you knew Miss Laws so long, did you not call upon her, and say you was glad you were going to be related to her - A. She was out of town.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18201028-68-person771">
                  JOHN 
                  MILLINGTON
               <interp inst="t18201028-68-person771" type="surname" value="MILLINGTON"></interp>
